Sure, here's an example solution to the 2-sum problem in JavaScript:

```
function twoSum(nums, target) {
  const map = new Map();

  for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    const complement = target - nums[i];
    if (map.has(complement)) {
      return [map.get(complement), i];
    }
    map.set(nums[i], i);
  }
  return [];
}
```

This function takes in an array of numbers `nums` and a target integer `target`, and returns an array of two indices that add up to `target`. It uses a hash table (implemented as a `Map` object in JavaScript) to store the indices of each number as it iterates through the array. If the complement of the current number (i.e. `target - nums[i]`) is already in the hash table, then we know we've found a pair of indices that add up to `target`.

To use this function, you can call it with an array of numbers and a target value, like so:

```
const nums = [2, 7, 11, 15];
const target = 9;
const indices = twoSum(nums, target);
console.log(indices); // [0, 1]
```

In this example, the function returns `[0, 1]`, because the values at indices `0` and `1` of the `nums` array add up to the `target` value of `9`.

